# Confidence: No public PoC known — pattern inferred from the
# CVE/advisory description only.
# No packet-capture (PCAP) data source is available to this pipeline —
# this pattern is NOT verified against captured exploit traffic.
#
# CVE-2026-63093 — Cursor for Windows 3.2.16 binary planting vulnerability.
# Attack vector: A crafted repository contains a malicious git.exe in its
# workspace root (or a directory on the DLL/binary search path). When the
# victim opens the repository in Cursor, the application automatically
# executes the workspace-resident git.exe instead of the system-installed
# binary, achieving arbitrary code execution [1][3][4].
#
# Network-observable signal: The exploit requires delivery of a crafted
# repository to the victim. The most realistic network-observable phase is
# the repository being cloned or downloaded over HTTP/HTTPS (e.g., a ZIP
# archive or tarball containing a git.exe at a suspicious path such as
# the workspace root or a git-related subdirectory). This rule looks for
# HTTP responses delivering a Windows PE executable (MZ header) at a path
# whose filename is "git.exe", which is anomalous for a legitimate software
# repository payload — legitimate git distributions are not delivered as
# bare binaries inside project repository archives.
#
# IMPORTANT ANALYST NOTES:
# 1. This rule targets the *delivery* phase, not in-host execution, because
#    the binary-planting exploitation itself produces no distinct network
#    traffic after repository open.
# 2. The match logic (MZ header in response body + git.exe in URI) is a
#    heuristic and will produce false positives for any legitimate HTTP
#    download of a git.exe binary. Tune $HOME_NET and whitelist known-good
#    Git distribution servers (e.g., git-scm.com, GitHub release CDNs)
#    before deploying in blocking mode.
# 3. Because no PCAP or PoC is available, analyst review and testing in a
#    lab environment are STRONGLY recommended before production deployment.
# 4. This is a PROPOSED DRAFT for analyst review — do not deploy without
#    independent validation.
# 5. MITRE technique: T1574.001 (Hijack Execution Flow: DLL/Binary Search
#    Order Hijacking) is the closest mapping for binary planting; T1195.002
#    (Supply Chain Compromise via software repositories) is also relevant.
#    "T1" priority tag from context noted [1][4].
# 6. CVE is 3 days old [1]; no CISA KEV listing confirmed at time of
#    rule generation — is_kev set to false accordingly.

alert http $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET any (
  msg:"THREATFORGE CVE-2026-63093 Cursor binary planting git.exe delivery attempt";
  flow:established,to_client;
  http.uri; content:"git.exe"; nocase; isdataat:!1,relative;
  file.data; content:"|4D 5A|"; offset:0; depth:2;
  reference:cve,2026-63093;
  metadata:mitre_technique_id T1574.001, is_kev false, status experimental;
  classtype:trojan-activity; sid:9000010; rev:1; )

